{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17630368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17630368"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:15:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:15:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17310"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17310"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.52,0,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10000"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69790"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10000"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17310"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55245"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7235"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23418"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23422"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23429"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69790"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA patient presents with numbness on the inner aspect of his thigh. There are a number of nerves that provide cutaneous sensation to the lower limb.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerves provides sensation at the medial aspect of the thigh?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Femoral","Obturator","Sciatic","Superficial fibular","Tibial"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eobturator nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for providing sensory innervation to the medial aspect of the thigh. It also supplies motor innervation to the adductor muscles of the thigh. In this scenario, the patient\u0027s symptoms of numbness in the medial thigh are consistent with obturator nerve involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efemoral nerve\u003C/strong\u003E primarily supplies the anterior thigh and provides sensation to the anterior and medial aspects of the leg via the saphenous nerve, but not the medial thigh above the knee.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esciatic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E does not provide sensory innervation to the medial thigh. It primarily innervates the posterior thigh and most of the lower leg and foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperficial fibular nerve\u003C/strong\u003E supplies sensation to the dorsum of the foot and does not innervate the thigh.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etibial nerve\u003C/strong\u003E provides sensation to the sole of the foot and does not innervate the thigh.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The obturator nerve provides sensory innervation to the medial thigh above the knee.","The femoral nerve primarily supplies the anterior thigh and medial leg.","The sciatic nerve does not provide sensory innervation to the medial thigh."],"references":["Sakellariou VI, Badilas NK, Mazis GA, Stavropoulos NA, Kotoulas HK, Kyriakopoulos S, Tagkalegkas I, Sofianos IP. Brachial plexus injuries in adults: evaluation and diagnostic approach. ISRN Orthop. 2014 Feb 9;2014:726103. doi: 10.1155/2014/726103. PMID: 24967130; PMCID: PMC4045362","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. El